<Layout title="Ch.3 — Limits and Continuity" favicon="∫">
  <main>

    <a href="/reading/calculus/" class="text-sm mb-4 inline-block">&larr; back to calculus</a>

    <h1>Limits and Continuity</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mb-6">Active Calculus (CC BY-SA) · <a href="https://activecalculus.org/">activecalculus.org</a></p>

    <div class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-5 mb-8 callout">
      <p class="text-lg" style="max-width:none">A <strong>limit</strong> captures what f(x) approaches as x approaches a, even if f(a) is undefined. The epsilon-delta definition makes "approaches" precise. Continuity means the limit equals the function value. The Intermediate Value Theorem is the payoff.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- SVG: function approaching a limit -->
    <div class="flex justify-center my-6">
      <svg viewBox="0 0 360 180" class="w-full max-w-sm" style="font-family: ui-monospace, monospace;">
        <!-- Axes -->
        <line x1="40" y1="150" x2="320" y2="150" stroke="#71717a" stroke-width="1" stroke-opacity="0.45"/>
        <line x1="60" y1="20" x2="60" y2="160" stroke="#71717a" stroke-width="1" stroke-opacity="0.45"/>
        <!-- Curve approaching but with hole at x=180 -->
        <path d="M 80 130 Q 130 90 170 60" fill="none" stroke="#60a5fa" stroke-width="2" stroke-opacity="0.7"/>
        <path d="M 190 60 Q 230 30 300 40" fill="none" stroke="#60a5fa" stroke-width="2" stroke-opacity="0.7"/>
        <!-- Open circle (hole) at the limit point -->
        <circle cx="180" cy="55" r="4" fill="#1a1a2e" stroke="#f59e0b" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-opacity="0.7"/>
        <!-- Dashed horizontal line to limit value -->
        <line x1="55" y1="55" x2="175" y2="55" stroke="#f59e0b" stroke-width="1" stroke-dasharray="4,3" stroke-opacity="0.4"/>
        <!-- Dashed vertical line to x=a -->
        <line x1="180" y1="55" x2="180" y2="150" stroke="#f59e0b" stroke-width="1" stroke-dasharray="4,3" stroke-opacity="0.4"/>
        <!-- Labels -->
        <text x="40" y="58" fill="#f59e0b" font-size="10" fill-opacity="0.6">L</text>
        <text x="180" y="165" text-anchor="middle" fill="#f59e0b" font-size="10" fill-opacity="0.6">a</text>
        <text x="250" y="30" fill="currentColor" font-size="10" fill-opacity="0.4">lim f(x) = L</text>
        <text x="250" y="42" fill="currentColor" font-size="9" fill-opacity="0.3">x&#x2192;a</text>
      </svg>
    </div>

    <!-- 1. Intuitive limits -->
    <h3>Intuitive limits</h3>
    <p>The limit of f(x) as x approaches a is L if f(x) gets arbitrarily close to L whenever x is sufficiently close to a (but not equal to a). We can test this numerically by plugging in values closer and closer to a.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; Limit of sin(x)/x as x -> 0
; f(0) is undefined (0/0), but the limit exists

(define (f x) (/ (sin x) x))

; Approach 0 from the right
(display "x=1.0:    ") (display (f 1.0)) (newline)
(display "x=0.1:    ") (display (f 0.1)) (newline)
(display "x=0.01:   ") (display (f 0.01)) (newline)
(display "x=0.001:  ") (display (f 0.001)) (newline)
(display "x=0.0001: ") (display (f 0.0001)) (newline)

; Approach 0 from the left
(display "x=-0.01:  ") (display (f -0.01)) (newline)
(display "x=-0.001: ") (display (f -0.001)) (newline)

(display "Limit = 1")
`} />

    <div class="python-block my-2" style="display:none">
      <Repl client:visible initialCode={`import math

def f(x): return math.sin(x) / x

for x in [1.0, 0.1, 0.01, 0.001, 0.0001]:
    print(f"f({x}) = {f(x):.8f}")

print("Limit as x -> 0 is 1")
`} />
    </div>


    <!-- 2. Epsilon-delta -->
    <h3>Epsilon-delta definition</h3>
    <p>For every &#x3B5; &gt; 0, there exists a &#x3B4; &gt; 0 such that |f(x) - L| &lt; &#x3B5; whenever 0 &lt; |x - a| &lt; &#x3B4;. This replaces "approaches" with a checkable inequality. &#x3B5; is the tolerance on the output; &#x3B4; is the tolerance on the input.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; Epsilon-delta: show that lim(2x+1) as x->3 = 7
; For any epsilon, we need delta such that
; |f(x) - 7| < epsilon when 0 < |x - 3| < delta
; |(2x+1) - 7| = |2x - 6| = 2|x-3| < epsilon
; So delta = epsilon/2 works.

(define (f x) (+ (* 2 x) 1))
(define L 7)
(define a 3)

(define (check-epsilon-delta epsilon)
  (let ((delta (/ epsilon 2)))
    ; Test a point just inside delta
    (let ((x (+ a (* delta 0.99))))
      (let ((error (abs (- (f x) L))))
        (display "eps=") (display epsilon)
        (display " delta=") (display delta)
        (display " |f(x)-L|=") (display (/ (round (* error 100000)) 100000))
        (display (if (< error epsilon) " OK" " FAIL"))
        (newline)))))

(check-epsilon-delta 1.0)
(check-epsilon-delta 0.1)
(check-epsilon-delta 0.01)
(check-epsilon-delta 0.001)
`} />

    <div class="python-block my-2" style="display:none">
      <Repl client:visible initialCode={`# Epsilon-delta: lim(2x+1) as x->3 = 7
# delta = epsilon/2 works because |(2x+1)-7| = 2|x-3|
def f(x): return 2*x + 1
L, a = 7, 3

for eps in [1.0, 0.1, 0.01, 0.001]:
    delta = eps / 2
    x = a + delta * 0.99
    error = abs(f(x) - L)
    status = "OK" if error < eps else "FAIL"
    print("eps={} delta={} |f(x)-L|={:.5f} {}".format(eps, delta, error, status))
`} />
    </div>


    <!-- 3. Squeeze theorem -->
    <h3>Squeeze theorem</h3>
    <p>If g(x) &#x2264; f(x) &#x2264; h(x) near a, and lim g(x) = lim h(x) = L, then lim f(x) = L. The classic example: -1 &#x2264; sin(x) &#x2264; 1, so -|x| &#x2264; x sin(1/x) &#x2264; |x|. As x approaches 0, both bounds go to 0, so x sin(1/x) goes to 0.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; Squeeze theorem: x*sin(1/x) -> 0 as x -> 0
; Because -|x| <= x*sin(1/x) <= |x|

(define (f x) (* x (sin (/ 1 x))))
(define (lower x) (- (abs x)))
(define (upper x) (abs x))

(define (show x)
  (display "x=") (display x)
  (display " lower=") (display (/ (round (* (lower x) 10000)) 10000))
  (display " f=") (display (/ (round (* (f x) 10000)) 10000))
  (display " upper=") (display (/ (round (* (upper x) 10000)) 10000))
  (newline))

(show 1.0)
(show 0.1)
(show 0.01)
(show 0.001)
(display "All three squeeze to 0")
`} />

    <div class="python-block my-2" style="display:none">
      <Repl client:visible initialCode={`import math

# Squeeze theorem: -|x| <= x*sin(1/x) <= |x|
def f(x): return x * math.sin(1/x)

for x in [1.0, 0.1, 0.01, 0.001]:
    print("x={} lower={:.4f} f={:.4f} upper={:.4f}".format(
        x, -abs(x), f(x), abs(x)))
print("All three squeeze to 0")
`} />
    </div>


    <!-- 4. Continuity -->
    <h3>Continuity</h3>
    <p>f is <strong>continuous</strong> at a if three things hold: f(a) exists, lim f(x) as x approaches a exists, and the limit equals f(a). Polynomials, sin, cos, exp are continuous everywhere on their domains. Rational functions are continuous except where the denominator is zero.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; Continuity check: f is continuous at a if lim f(x) = f(a)

; Continuous: f(x) = x^2 at x = 2
(define (f x) (* x x))
(display "f(2) = ") (display (f 2)) (newline)
(display "f(1.99) = ") (display (f 1.99)) (newline)
(display "f(2.01) = ") (display (f 2.01)) (newline)
(display "Continuous: limit = f(2) = 4") (newline) (newline)

; Discontinuous: g(x) = 1/x at x = 0
; g(0) is undefined, so g is not continuous at 0
(display "g(0.001) = ") (display (/ 1 0.001)) (newline)
(display "g(-0.001) = ") (display (/ 1 -0.001)) (newline)
(display "Left and right limits disagree: not continuous")
`} />

    <div class="python-block my-2" style="display:none">
      <Repl client:visible initialCode={`# Continuity: lim f(x) must equal f(a)
# Continuous: f(x) = x^2 at x = 2
f = lambda x: x**2
print("f(2) =", f(2))
print("f(1.99) =", f(1.99))
print("f(2.01) =", f(2.01))
print("Continuous: limit = f(2) = 4")
print()

# Discontinuous: g(x) = 1/x at x = 0
print("g(0.001) =", 1/0.001)
print("g(-0.001) =", 1/-0.001)
print("Left and right limits disagree: not continuous")
`} />
    </div>


    <!-- 5. IVT -->
    <h3>Intermediate Value Theorem</h3>
    <p>If f is continuous on [a,b] and f(a) &lt; c &lt; f(b), then there exists some x in (a,b) where f(x) = c. Geometrically: a continuous curve that goes from below c to above c must cross c somewhere. This is how we prove roots exist.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; IVT: if f is continuous and changes sign, there's a root
; Use bisection to find where x^2 - 2 = 0 (i.e., sqrt(2))

(define (f x) (- (* x x) 2))

(define (bisect lo hi n)
  (if (= n 0)
      (let ((mid (/ (+ lo hi) 2)))
        (display "root ~ ") (display mid) (newline)
        (display "f(root) ~ ") (display (f mid)))
      (let ((mid (/ (+ lo hi) 2)))
        (if (< (* (f lo) (f mid)) 0)
            (bisect lo mid (- n 1))
            (bisect mid hi (- n 1))))))

(display "f(1) = ") (display (f 1)) (newline)   ; -1
(display "f(2) = ") (display (f 2)) (newline)   ;  2
(display "Sign change: root exists in (1,2)") (newline)
(bisect 1.0 2.0 30)
`} />

    <div class="python-block my-2" style="display:none">
      <Repl client:visible initialCode={`# IVT + bisection to find sqrt(2)
def f(x): return x**2 - 2

lo, hi = 1.0, 2.0
print("f(1) =", f(1), " f(2) =", f(2))
print("Sign change: root exists in (1,2)")

for _ in range(30):
    mid = (lo + hi) / 2
    if f(lo) * f(mid) < 0:
        hi = mid
    else:
        lo = mid

print("root ~", mid)
print("f(root) ~", f(mid))
`} />
    </div>


